<DOC><DOCNO> AP890927-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0229EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BAT-MarshallField     09-27 0273</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BAT-Marshall Field,0282</SECOND><HEAD>Management Buyout Offer Planned for Chicago Retailer</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Britain-BAT, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The management of Marshall Field and Co. will bidto buy the department store chain, which would be sold under amajor restructuring proposed by its British parent, the chain'schairman said.   Philip B. Miller said Tuesday that management intends to make``an aggressive buyout offer'' in response to the announcement byLondon-based BAT Industries PLC that it will sell its U.S.retailing operations in an effort to fight a hostile takeover byfinancier Sir James Goldsmith.   Field's chairman and chief executive officer said in a statementthat management will make a ``competitive offer which will meet thefiduciary requirements of BAT's board, ensuring fair value to BATshareholders.'' He did not place a dollar value on it.   Marshall Field has 24 stores in Illinois, Ohio, Wisconsin andTexas that employ 13,000 people. The chain opened its flagshipstore in Chicago in 1856 as one of the nation's first and mostsuccessful department stores.   The company is projecting record sales and earnings for 1989,Miller said in a statement.   He said the chain posted its first $1 billion sales year in in1988 with a profit of $83 million.   Under a management buyout, Miller said the company ``wouldcontinue to be operated at the highly productive level that hascontributed to the success of the management team in the last fiveyears.''   BAT announced earlier Tuesday that it planned to sell its U.S.retailing operations _ including Saks Fifth Avenue, MarshallField's and two regional retailers _ and concentrate on its tobaccoand financial services businesses.</TEXT></DOC>